net.sf.mmm.util.datatype.api.phone

Class PhoneCountryCode

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractDatatype
      • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractSimpleDatatypeBase<V>
        • net.sf.mmm.util.lang.api.AbstractSimpleDatatype<Integer>
          • net.sf.mmm.util.datatype.api.phone.PhoneCountryCode
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Serializable, AttributeReadValue<Integer>, Datatype, SimpleDatatype<Integer>

    public final class PhoneCountryCode
extends AbstractSimpleDatatype<Integer>
    This class is a Datatype that represents the country code for a phone number. The country code is the prefix of the phone number that identifies the country where the phone is located.
    If formatted as string the country code is typically prefixed by "+". This stands for the actual InternationalCallPrefix.
    ATTENTION:
    The international country codes are historically grown. Therefore it does not actually perform its purpose to identify a country as some countries share the same country code (e.g. USA, Canada, and Puerto Rico all have "1"). Further, the length of country codes is not normalized. The length varies from 1 to 4 (excluding the InternationalCallPrefix). Additionally, some country codes are prefixes of other country codes. Since the zero of the area code is suppressed, the country code of a phone number given as string can only be determined by knowledge of the area codes that has to be up-to-date.
    Since:
    1.0.0
    Author:
    Joerg Hohwiller (hohwille at users.sourceforge.net)

        public String toString()
        Description copied from interface: Datatype
        Returns the official String representation of this Datatype. While the general contract of Object.toString() is very weak and mainly used for debugging, the contract here is very strong. The returned String has to be suitable for end-users and official output to any kind of sink.
